Theoretical Background¶

Seasonality in time series refers to the presence of regular and predictable patterns or cycles that repeat over a fixed period, such as days, months, or years. It is always of a fixed and known frequency, associated with some aspect of the calendar. The provided search results emphasize the impact of seasonality on aviation, particularly in the context of airport traffic, airline efficiency, and tourism. The seasonal variations in air traffic demand can significantly affect airport and airline operations, as well as the tourism industry. Understanding and accounting for seasonality in air traffic data is crucial for various analyses, including demand forecasting, capacity planning, and resource management. The search results also highlight the use of time series analysis to detect and handle seasonality, which is essential for building accurate and reliable forecasting models.

Our Project¶

In our analysis, we have focused on exploring the seasonality in flight data, particularly in the context of airport traffic and airline operations from the U.S. Airline Traffic Data. We have applied various descriptive techniques to understand the patterns and trends within the flight series. These techniques include smoothing methods like Holt-Winter models, harmonic analysis, and neural networks. By employing these techniques, we aimed to uncover the underlying seasonal variations, identify trends, and develop accurate forecasting models for both domestic and international flights.

Data split 80%-20%¶

The first step of this project was to split the data into train and test sets. We used the training data to train the models, and then forecast with the "test data". Before splitting the data, we needed to transform the variables into numeric format and combine the "Year" and "Month" into a single variable called "Date". Additionally, we created the index "MS" to impute where the month starts. The train set consists of 80% of the data, covering from January 2003 to July 2016, while the test set comprises the remaining 20%, covering from August 2016 to September 2019.

# Convert object-type columns to numeric format
for col in df.columns:
    if df[col].dtype == 'object':

The first thing to note is that the number of domestic flights over the years is much bigger than the international flights.

The decrease in the total number of domestic flights in the US since 2008, while the number of international flights increase in trend, can be attributed to several factors. One possible explanation is the impact of the 2008 financial crisis, which led to a decrease in domestic air travel demand due to economic decline and reduced consumer spending. Additionally, changes in consumer preferences, such as a shift towards alternative modes of transportation for domestic travel, could also contribute to this trend. Furthermore, the rise of teleconferencing and remote work may have reduced the need for domestic business travel, while international travel demand increase a little bit. These factors, among others, may have influenced the diverging trends in domestic and international flight numbers.

Holt-Winters Forecasting¶

The Holt-Winters model is a forecasting method that is used for data exhibiting both a trend and a seasonal variation. It comprises the forecast equation and three smoothing equations: one for the level ($a_t$), one for the trend ($b_t$), and one for the seasonal component ($S_t$), with corresponding smoothing parameters $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$. The model is defined by its three order parameters: $\alpha$ (the coefficient for the level smoothing), $\beta$ (the coefficient for the trend smoothing), and $\gamma$ (the coefficient for the seasonal smoothing). It applies triple exponential smoothing for level, trend, and seasonal components. The method can handle both additive and multiplicative seasonality, where each season changes by a constant number or a factor, respectively. In our work we have used the additive model because is useful when the seasonal variation is relatively constant over time.

The seasonal component exhibits a repetitive pattern resembling small mountains, indicating periodic fluctuations over time. The residual component shows points scattered around the line at 0, with only two points noticeably deviating from the rest, located in the early years. These observations suggest that the time series data contains a trend, seasonal variations, and some residual noise, with notable deviations captured by the residual component.

We used the additive model so we can come up with the regular equation form:

$\hat{z}_{t+h} + hb_t + S_{t-p+(h−1)modp}$

where $a_t$ is the level, $b_t$ is the trend and $S_t$ is the seasonal component. We can defined the formulas in the following way:

  • $a_t = α(z_t - S_{t-p}) + (1-α)(a_{t-1} + b_{t-1})$

  • $b_t = β(a_t - a_{t-1}) + (1-β)b_{t-1}$

  • $S_t = γ(z_t - a_t) + (1-γ)S_{t-p}$

In our time series (total of Flights):

  • $a_t = 0.74(flight_t - S_{t-12}) + 0.26(a_{t-1} + b_{t-1})$

  • $b_t = b_{t-1}$

  • $S_t = 1.16(flight_t - a_t) - 0.15S_{t-12}$

Neural networks¶

Neural networks, inspired by the brain's structure, are powerful tools for analyzing complex relationships in data. In time series forecasting, Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, a type of artificial neural network, stand out for their ability to capture temporal patterns and make accurate predictions based on historical data. By leveraging LSTM layers, these networks excel at learning from past observations to forecast future values. The program seen in class and used in this project, utilizes Keras to build an LSTM model tailored for time series forecasting, demonstrating how neural networks can effectively predict trends in sequential data.

Flights¶

In [ ]:
%%capture
# Scale the data using MinMaxScaler for only the 'Flt' variable
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0, 1))
train_flt_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(train_data[['Flt']])
test_flt_scaled = scaler.transform(test_data[['Flt']])
# Prepare the training data for LSTM using only the 'Flt' variable
X_flt_train, y_flt_train = [], []
for i in range(12, len(train_flt_scaled)):
    X_flt_train.append(train_flt_scaled[i-12:i, 0])
    y_flt_train.append(train_flt_scaled[i, 0])
X_flt_train, y_flt_train = np.array(X_flt_train), np.array(y_flt_train)

# Reshape the data for LSTM
X_flt_train = np.reshape(X_flt_train, (X_flt_train.shape[0], X_flt_train.shape[1], 1))

# Build and compile the LSTM model
model = Sequential([
    LSTM(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X_flt_train.shape[1], 1)),
    LSTM(50),
    Dense(1)
])
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')

# Train the model
model.fit(X_flt_train, y_flt_train, epochs=100, batch_size=32)

# Prepare the test data for prediction
X_flt_test = []
for i in range(len(test_flt_scaled) - 12, len(test_flt_scaled)):
    X_flt_test.append(test_flt_scaled[i-12:i, 0])
X_flt_test = np.array(X_flt_test)

# Reshape the data for LSTM
X_flt_test = np.reshape(X_flt_test, (X_flt_test.shape[0], X_flt_test.shape[1], 1))

# Predict the test data
flt_predictions2_scaled = model.predict(X_flt_test)

# Inverse transform the predictions to get the actual passenger values
flt_predictions2 = scaler.inverse_transform(flt_predictions2_scaled)

test_int_scaled = scaler_int.transform(test_data[['Int_Flt']])

# Define a function to prepare data for LSTM
def prepare_data(data_scaled):
    X_train, y_train = [], []
    for i in range(12, len(data_scaled)):
        X_train.append(data_scaled[i-12:i, 0])
        y_train.append(data_scaled[i, 0])
    X_train, y_train = np.array(X_train), np.array(y_train)
    X_train = np.reshape(X_train, (X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], 1))
    return X_train, y_train

# Prepare the training data for domestic flights
X_dom_train, y_dom_train = prepare_data(train_dom_scaled)

# Prepare the training data for international flights
X_int_train, y_int_train = prepare_data(train_int_scaled)

# Build and compile the LSTM model for domestic flights
model_dom = Sequential([
    LSTM(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X_dom_train.shape[1], 1)),
    LSTM(50),
    Dense(1)
])
model_dom.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')

# Build and compile the LSTM model for international flights
model_int = Sequential([
    LSTM(50, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X_int_train.shape[1], 1)),
    LSTM(50),
    Dense(1)
])
model_int.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')

# Train the LSTM model for domestic flights
model_dom.fit(X_dom_train, y_dom_train, epochs=100, batch_size=32)

# Train the LSTM model for international flights
model_int.fit(X_int_train, y_int_train, epochs=100, batch_size=32)

# Prepare the test data for prediction for domestic flights
X_dom_test = []
for i in range(len(test_dom_scaled) - 12, len(test_dom_scaled)):
    X_dom_test.append(test_dom_scaled[i-12:i, 0])
X_dom_test = np.array(X_dom_test)
X_dom_test = np.reshape(X_dom_test, (X_dom_test.shape[0], X_dom_test.shape[1], 1))

# Prepare the test data for prediction for international flights
X_int_test = []
for i in range(len(test_int_scaled) - 12, len(test_int_scaled)):
    X_int_test.append(test_int_scaled[i-12:i, 0])
X_int_test = np.array(X_int_test)
X_int_test = np.reshape(X_int_test, (X_int_test.shape[0], X_int_test.shape[1], 1))

# Predict the test data for domestic flights
dom_predictions_scaled = model_dom.predict(X_dom_test)
dom_predictions = scaler_dom.inverse_transform(dom_predictions_scaled)

# Predict the test data for international flights
int_predictions_scaled = model_int.predict(X_int_test)
int_predictions = scaler_int.inverse_transform(int_predictions_scaled)

Harmonic analysis¶

The Harmonic analysis consist in modelling seasonal fluctuations, assuming that the periodic patterns (months) can be represented as a combination of sine and cosine functions. This functions are:

  • $sin(\frac{2πt}{s})$
  • $cos(\frac{2πt}{s})$

$s$ is called period of the periodic function. And $f = \frac{1}{s}$ is calle frequency. Finally $ω = 2πf = \frac{2π}{s}$ is the angular frequency.

In this series the frequency is monthly so the value of $s = 12$ and $f = 1/12 = 0.083$ and the function has passed: $8.3\%$ of a full cycle. The angular frequency is $ω = \frac{2π}{12} = \frac{π}{6}$. The angular frequency represents the speed at which the oscillating object completes one full cycle. This indicates how quickly the number of flights fluctuates from one month to another throughout the year.

Flights¶

We need to substract the trend to isolate the remaining variations in the data that are not captured by the trend component. Then, we calculate our time index ($t$) and we used it in the $sin$ and $cos$ function. Additionally, we reset the index to match it with the X's matrix indices.

In [ ]:
# Subtract trend from 'Flt'
flt = train_data['Flt'] - dec_result_flt.trend

# Create time index
f = np.arange(len(flt)) + 1

# Create sine and cosine components
sine = np.sin(f * 2 * np.pi / 12)
cosine = np.cos(f * 2 * np.pi / 12)

# Create the design matrix
X = pd.DataFrame({'sine': sine, 'cosine': cosine})

# Add constant to the model

# Resetting indices to match

# Fit the linear regression model
model = sm.OLS(flt, X)
flt_results_harmonic = model.fit()

In this periodogram, we can identify the dominant frequency, which is approximately at the frequency $≈ 0.08$, corresponding to a cycle of $\frac{1}{0.08} \approx 12.5$ months. This suggests that the dominant frequency of 0.0859 cycles per month might correspond to a repeating pattern approximately every year. The second maximum of the spectral density is in 0.4172 cycles per month which might correspond to a more frequent pattern, occurring approximately every 2 month.

MSE_dom_flt_harmonic = mean_squared_error(dom_flt_detrended, dom_flt_fitted_series)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE) for Domestic Flights (Harmonic Model):", MSE_dom_flt_harmonic)

# Sort the spectrum values in descending order for international flights
sorted_indices_int_flt = np.argsort(spectrum_int_flt)[::-1]  # Get sorted indices in descending order
max_indices_int_flt = sorted_indices_int_flt[:2]  # Get the indices of the top 2 maximum values

# Get the maximum spectrum values and corresponding frequencies for international flights
max_values_int_flt = spectrum_int_flt[max_indices_int_flt]
corresponding_freqs_int_flt = freqs_int_flt[max_indices_int_flt]

# Print the maximum values and corresponding frequencies for international flights
print("\nMaximum values of periodogram for International Flights:", max_values_int_flt)
print("Corresponding frequencies for International Flights:", corresponding_freqs_int_flt)

# Calculate Mean Squared Error (MSE) for harmonic model for international flights
MSE_int_flt_harmonic = mean_squared_error(int_flt_detrended, int_flt_fitted_series)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE) for International Flights (Harmonic Model):", MSE_int_flt_harmonic)

Not only for the domestic flight but also for the international flights, the dominant frequency appears in approximately 0.086 cycles per month. We can conclude that both series have repeating pattern approximately every year, so both time series has a strong seasonal that repeat aprroximatly every year. Finally, we have the secondary peak that means a more frequent pattern, occurring approximately every 2 month for domestic flights and every 6 month for international flights.

Conclusion¶

In summary, our project has successfully explored seasonality in flight data using various techniques like Holt-Winter models, harmonic analysis, and neural networks. Our evaluation based on Mean Squared Error (MSE) revealed that the Harmonic Regression model performed best for total and domestic flights, while the Holt-Winters model excelled in forecasting international flights. This highlights the importance of selecting tailored models for different data characteristics. Our findings emphasize the need for precise modeling to enhance forecasting accuracy in airline operations.
